Movements, Home range and Social organization.
The False Killer Whale is highly social and travels in groups of 20-100 individuals, although larger groups have been reported. Mass strandings have occasionally been in excess of 1000 individuals. Studies of social structure in populations of False Killer Whales off Hawaii indicate that individuals form strong social bonds, and long-term associations lasting up to 15 years are common. As one of the cetacean species known to often mass strand, these strong social bonds come as no surprise. Strong sociality is a factor implicated in mass strandings because a navigational error made by a single individual is likely to be followed by every other individual in the group in a kind of social conformism. The False Killer Whale has also been observed associated with other delphinid species including the Common Bottlenose Dolphin (7 
Tursiops truncatus
) and the Rough-toothed Dolphin (
Steno bredanensis
). Little is known about movement and migratory patterns of the False Killer Whale, but a population off Hawaii appears to show strong site fidelity to the archipelago as a whole (although individuals may move substantial distances, up to 283 km, among the islands).
